Brother Ron,<br><br>
Only a small percentage of the troops in Viet Nam were &quot;on the line&quot;. The whole country was a combat zone. You could've bought it just as easily on the streets of Saigon as in the DMZ. There's no shame in making the best of a bad situation. The fact that you were there, got back safely, and then volunteered for a second tour, makes you a hell of a lot more of a man than that capon in the White House. <br>
Don't forget that many of the line troops volunteered for combat duty. They believed all that bullshit about &quot;protecting democracy&quot;. That is not why we were there. We were supporting one of the most corrupt regimes in the world. We were there for commerce. We were there for oil, rubber, drugs, Dow chemical, Pacific Architects and Engineers, and God knows what all else. Our government didn't give a shit about preserving democracy in Viet Nam. There was never any democracy in Viet Nam to preserve. We ran out of there in '74 with our tail between our legs, leaving our Vietnamese allies holding the bag-except for Thieu and Ky, of course.<br>
Shit Pard, you were Audie Murphy compared with the U.S as a whole. Give yourself a pat on the back for being smart enough and lucky enough to have not gotten your balls shot off(although, with no balls, you could have become President).<br><br>
